Good leadership
Nothing pains more than the concept of equality of vote. And, with democracy the rule of the majority, whether ignorant or informed, they will always have their way.
Yet most Kenyans don’t understand why they vote or the responsibilities of their leaders. For instance, instead of demanding of a senator sound legislation, they would ask, “How many schools has he constructed?” Do they give handouts or attend funerals?
What do we do? Limit those who vote? I believe not. All should be allowed to vote. But, to save the voter, let’s think hard about who makes a leader. This is where political parties come in handy.
A seminal responsibility of political parties is grooming leaders. They should stop polarising the country by offering to the voter clueless and incompetent candidates.



